        "body": "After twenty-two years and three genealogical chapters (chapters 36, 46), the narrator finally gives Jacob what the reader has been waiting for since Genesis 37: the face of the son he believed dead. The scene is spare and overwhelming. Joseph prepares his chariot — no small act; a chariot was the vehicle of Egyptian power, and Joseph is second only to Pharaoh (Genesis 41:43). He does not send a delegation. He goes himself, driving up to Goshen to meet a 130-year-old man who traveled by wagon.\n\nJudah is sent ahead (46:28) not by accident. From chapters 37 onward, Judah has been the son whose trajectory has been most dramatically reversed — from the one who proposed selling Joseph (37:26-27), to the one who offered himself as surety for Benjamin (43:9), to the one who gave the speech that broke Joseph's composure (44:33-34). By sending Judah as the advance party to Joseph, Jacob enacts a recognition that the brother most responsible for the original rupture has become the instrument of the family's reconciliation. Canonically, Judah's role here anticipates the scepter promise of 49:10: the tribe of Judah will be the channel through whom God works.\n\nThe reunion itself is narrated in two verbs and one clause: 'he fell on his neck and wept on his neck a long time' (46:29). The narrator does not linger; the economy of language is itself the point. Twenty-two years of grief do not need more words. Jacob's response — 'Now let me die, since I have seen your face, that you are still alive' (46:30) — is theologically precise. The word 'now' (*paam*, 'this time,' 'at this moment') marks the arrival of what he had despaired of seeing. Jacob does not say he wants to die of joy; he says he has now received the one thing he had given up as permanently lost. His capacity for desire has been satisfied. What Jonathan Edwards called the 'resting of the soul in its object' — here it is: a father who has seen his son's face.\n\nSwindoll notes that the reunion at Goshen is the moment where the Joseph narrative's long arc of providence becomes visible. What looked like abandonment (Genesis 37), what looked like divine silence (Genesis 39-40), what looked like the death of both the dreamer and the dream — all of it converges on a road outside Goshen where a chariot-driving prime minister weeps on an old shepherd's neck."
